 of the peace in little Webber's Prairie. Eyewitness to so much Texas history, Smithwick recounts his life and adventures in a simple, straightforward style, with a wry sense of humor. His keen memory for detail—what the people wore, what they ate, how they worked and played— vividly evokes the sights, sounds, and smells of the frontier. First published in part by the Dallas Morning News, Smithwick's recollections gained such popularity that they were published in book form, as The Evolution of a State, in 1900. This new edition of a Texas classic makes widely available for the first time in many years this "best of all books dealing with life in early Texas."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezTexas. 0aFrontier and pioneer life-Texas. 0aPioneerszTexasvBiography. 0aSmithwick, Noah,-1808-1899. 0aTexas-History-To 1846. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh1 aShawl, Charles.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72043540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292749467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292749467/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK